lines.value: this situation varies in unusual conformations of dna within the cell see below but the major and minor grooves are always named to reflect the differences in size that would be seen if the dna is twisted back into the ordinary b form

lines.value: in a dna double helix each type of nucleobase on one strand normally interacts with just one type of nucleobase on the other strand
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: this is called complementary base pairing
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: here purines form hydrogen bonds to pyrimidines with a bonding only to t and c bonding only to g this arrangement of two nucleotides binding together across the double helix is called a base pair
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: as hydrogen bonds are not covalent they can be broken and rejoined relatively easily
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the two strands of dna in a double helix can therefore be pulled apart like a zipper either by a mechanical force or high temperature
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: as a result of this complementarity all the information in the double stranded sequence of a dna helix is duplicated on each strand which is vital in dna replication
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: indeed this reversible and specific interaction between complementary base pairs is critical for all the functions of dna in living organisms
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: <div class="thumb tright style="background:#f9f9f9 border:1px solid ccc margin:0.5em;"> <div style="border none width:282px;"><div class="thumbcaption">top a gc base pair with three hydrogen bonds
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: bottom an at base pair with two hydrogen bonds
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: non covalent hydrogen bonds between the pairs are shown as dashed lines
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the two types of base pairs form different numbers of hydrogen bonds at forming two hydrogen bonds and gc forming three hydrogen bonds see figures left
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: dna with high gc content is more stable than dna with low gc content
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: although it is often stated that this is due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond this is incorrect
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: dna with high gc content is more stable due to intra strand base stacking interactions
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: as noted above most dna molecules are actually two polymer strands bound together in a helical fashion by noncovalent bonds this double stranded structure dsdna is maintained largely by the intrastrand base stacking interactions which are strongest for g,c stacks
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the two strands can come apart - a process known as melting - to form two ss dna molecules
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: melting occurs when conditions favor ssdna such conditions are high temperature low salt and high ph low ph also melts dna but since dna is unstable due to acid depurination low ph is rarely used
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the stability of the dsdna form depends not only on the gc content % g,c basepairs but also on sequence since stacking is sequence specific and also length longer molecules are more stable
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the stability can be measured in various ways a common way is the melting temperature which is the temperature at which 50% of the ds molecules are converted to ss molecules melting temperature is dependent on ionic strength and the concentration of dna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: as a result it is both the percentage of gc base pairs and the overall length of a dna double helix that determine the strength of the association between the two strands of dna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: long dna helices with a high gc content have stronger interacting strands while short helices with high at content have weaker interacting strands
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in biology parts of the dna double helix that need to separate easily such as the tataat pribnow box in some promoters tend to have a high at content making the strands easier to pull apart
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in the laboratory the strength of this interaction can be measured by finding the temperature required to break the hydrogen bonds their melting temperature also called t m value
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: when all the base pairs in a dna double helix melt the strands separate and exist in solution as two entirely independent molecules
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these single stranded dna molecules ssdna have no single common shape but some conformations are more stable than others
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: a dna sequence is called sense if its sequence is the same as that of a messenger rna copy that is translated into protein
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the sequence on the opposite strand is called the antisense sequence
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: both sense and antisense sequences can exist on different parts of the same strand of dna i.e both strands contain both sense and antisense sequences
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes antisense rna sequences are produced but the functions of these rnas are not entirely clear
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: one proposal is that antisense rnas are involved in regulating gene expression through rna rna base pairing
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: a few dna sequences in prokaryotes and eukaryotes and more in plasmids and viruses blur the distinction between sense and antisense strands by having overlapping genes
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in these cases some dna sequences do double duty encoding one protein when read along one strand and a second protein when read in the opposite direction along the other strand
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in bacteria this overlap may be involved in the regulation of gene transcription while in viruses overlapping genes increase the amount of information that can be encoded within the small viral genome
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: dna can be twisted like a rope in a process called dna supercoiling
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: with dna in its relaxed state a strand usually circles the axis of the double helix once every 10.4 base pairs but if the dna is twisted the strands become more tightly or more loosely wound
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: if the dna is twisted in the direction of the helix this is positive supercoiling and the bases are held more tightly together
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: if they are twisted in the opposite direction this is negative supercoiling and the bases come apart more easily
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in nature most dna has slight negative supercoiling that is introduced by enzymes called topoisomerases
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these enzymes are also needed to relieve the twisting stresses introduced into dna strands during processes such as transcription and dna replication
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: dna exists in many possible conformations that include a dna b dna and z dna forms although only b dna and z dna have been directly observed in functional organisms
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the conformation that dna adopts depends on the hydration level dna sequence the amount and direction of supercoiling chemical modifications of the bases the type and concentration of metal ions as well as the presence of polyamines in solution
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the first published reports of a dna x ray diffraction patterns- and also b dna used analyses based on patterson transforms that provided only a limited amount of structural information for oriented fibers of dna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: an alternate analysis was then proposed by wilkins et al in 1953 for the in vivo b dna x ray diffraction scattering patterns of highly hydrated dna fibers in terms of squares of bessel functions
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in the same journal james d watson and francis crick presented their molecular modeling analysis of the dna x ray diffraction patterns to suggest that the structure was a double helix
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: although the b dna form is most common under the conditions found in cells it is not a well defined conformation but a family of related dna conformations that occur at the high hydration levels present in living cells
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: their corresponding x ray diffraction and scattering patterns are characteristic of molecular paracrystals with a significant degree of disorder
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: compared to b dna the a dna form is a wider right handed spiral with a shallow wide minor groove and a narrower deeper major groove
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the a form occurs under non physiological conditions in partially dehydrated samples of dna while in the cell it may be produced in hybrid pairings of dna and rna strands as well as in enzyme dna complexes
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: segments of dna where the bases have been chemically modified by methylation may undergo a larger change in conformation and adopt the z form
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: here the strands turn about the helical axis in a left handed spiral the opposite of the more common b form
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these unusual structures can be recognized by specific z dna binding proteins and may be involved in the regulation of transcription
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: for a number of years exobiologists have proposed the existence of a shadow biosphere a postulated microbial biosphere of earth that uses radically different biochemical and molecular processes than currently known life
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: one of the proposals was the existence of lifeforms that use arsenic instead of phosphorus in dna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: a december 2010 nasa press conference stated that the bacterium gfaj 1 which has evolved in an arsenic rich environment is the first terrestrial lifeform found which may have this ability
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the bacterium was found in mono lake east of yosemite national park
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: gfaj 1 is a rod shaped extremophile bacterium in the family halomonadaceae that when starved of phosphorus may be capable of incorporating the usually poisonous element arsenic in its dna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: this discovery may lend weight to the long standing idea that extraterrestrial life could have a different chemical makeup from life on earth
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the research was carried out by a team led by felisa wolfe simon a geomicrobiologist and geobiochemist a postdoctoral fellow of the nasa astrobiology institute with arizona state university
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: this finding has however faced strong criticism from the scientific community scientists have argued that there is no evidence that arsenic is actually incorporated into biomolecules
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: independent conformation of this finding has also not yet been possible
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: at the ends of the linear chromosomes are specialized regions of dna called telomeres
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the main function of these regions is to allow the cell to replicate chromosome ends using the enzyme telomerase as the enzymes that normally replicate dna cannot copy the extreme 3 ends of chromosomes
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these specialized chromosome caps also help protect the dna ends and stop the dna repair systems in the cell from treating them as damage to be corrected
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in human cells telomeres are usually lengths of single stranded dna containing several thousand repeats of a simple ttaggg sequence
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these guanine rich sequences may stabilize chromosome ends by forming structures of stacked sets of four base units rather than the usual base pairs found in other dna molecules
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: here four guanine bases form a flat plate and these flat four base units then stack on top of each other to form a stable g quadruplex structure
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: these structures are stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the edges of the bases and chelation of a metal ion in the centre of each four base unit
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: other structures can also be formed with the central set of four bases coming from either a single strand folded around the bases or several different parallel strands each contributing one base to the central structure
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in addition to these stacked structures telomeres also form large loop structures called telomere loops or t loops
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: here the single stranded dna curls around in a long circle stabilized by telomere binding proteins
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: at the very end of the t loop the single stranded telomere dna is held onto a region of double stranded dna by the telomere strand disrupting the double helical dna and base pairing to one of the two strands
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: this triple stranded structure is called a displacement loop or d loop
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: in dna fraying occurs when non complementary regions exist at the end of an otherwise complementary double strand of dna

lines.value: however branched dna can occur if a third strand of dna is introduced and contains adjoining regions able to hybridize with the frayed regions of the pre existing double strand

lines.value: although the simplest example of branched dna involves only three strands of dna complexes involving additional strands and multiple branches are also possible

lines.value: due to the volatility of elemental nitrogen and its common compounds with hydrogen and oxygen nitrogen is far less common on the rocky planets of the inner solar system and it is a relatively rare element on earth as a whole
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: however as on earth nitrogen and its compounds occur commonly as gases in the atmospheres of planets and moons that have atmospheres
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: many industrially important compounds such as ammonia nitric acid organic nitrates propellants and explosives and cyanides contain nitrogen
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the extremely strong bond in elemental nitrogen dominates nitrogen chemistry causing difficulty for both organisms and industry in converting or fixing the into useful compounds but at the same time causing release of large amounts of often useful energy when the compounds burn explode or decay back into nitrogen gas
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: synthetically produced ammonia and nitrates are key industrial fertilizers and fertilizer nitrates are key pollutants in causing the eutrophication of water systems
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: outside their major uses as fertilizers and energy stores nitrogen compounds are versitile organics
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen is part of materials as diverse as kevlar fabric and cyanoacrylate super glue
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen is a constituent of molecules in every major pharmacological drug class including the antibiotics
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: many drugs are mimics or prodrugs of natural nitrogen containing signal molecules for example the organic nitrates nitroglycerin and nitroprusside control blood pressure by being metabolized to natural nitric oxide
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: plant alkaloids often defense chemicals contain nitrogen by definition and thus many notable nitrogen containing drugs such as caffeine and morphine are either alkaloids or synthetic mimics that act as many plant alkaloids do upon receptors of animal neurotransmitters for example synthetic amphetamines
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen occurs in all organisms primarily in amino acids and thus proteins and also in the nucleic acids dna and rna
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the human body contains about 3% by weight of nitrogen the fourth most abundant element in the body after oxygen carbon and hydrogen
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the nitrogen cycle describes movement of the element from the air into the biosphere and organic compounds then back into the atmosphere
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen is formally considered to have been discovered by scottish physician daniel rutherford in 1772 who called it noxious air or fixed air
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: the fact that there was constituent of air that does not support combustion was clear to rutherford
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen was also studied at about the same time by carl wilhelm scheele henry cavendish and joseph priestley who referred to it as burnt air or phlogisticated air
lines.name: Yoruba

lines.value: nitrogen gas was inert enough that antoine lavoisier referred to it as "" or azote from the greek word azotos meaning lifeless

lines.value: in it animals died and flames were extinguished

lines.value: luiz inacio lula da silva (; ojoibi 27 october 1945 o gbajumo gege bi lula luiz inacio da silva was lula's full birth name which he used from 1945 to 1982 but he has been known as lula since childhood the nickname itself is a hypocoristic for luiz with consonantal reduplication

lines.value: consequently lula became the name by which he was known throughout his career as a metallurgical worker and as he emerged in the national scene as a union leader and for all his political life

lines.value: in 1982 in order to run for governorship of the state of sao paulo lula changed his legal name adding the nickname lula by which he was nationally known

lines.value: under brazilian electoral laws at the time one could only use one's legal name to run for public office
